  "voiceover": "I'm going to read you a passage, and I want you to guess the year it was written. He was despised and rejected by men — a man of sorrows, and acquainted with grief. But he was pierced for our transgressions, crushed for our iniquities; and with his wounds we are healed. Like a lamb led to the slaughter, he did not open his mouth. And they made his grave with the wicked — and with a rich man in his death. So what year? This is not the Gospels. It's Isaiah 53, written centuries before Jesus was born. And we can prove the date: the Dead Sea Scrolls gave us a complete copy of Isaiah from about 125 BC — over a century before Christ. No one edited it after the fact. Now look at that last line: a criminal's death, and a rich man's grave. Jesus was crucified between two criminals, and buried in the tomb of Joseph of Arimathea — a rich man. Here's the honest part: many Jewish readers understand the Servant as the nation Israel — a sincere, longstanding reading, and Isaiah 53's meaning is genuinely debated. So this isn't a mathematical proof. It's a portrait, sketched centuries early, that comes into startling focus on one face. Coincidence, or providence? You decide.",
